<br>
I disagree, though I appreciate the fact that you’re maintaining a civil and pleasant tone in this discussion.  The language I quoted above is more than “colorful” – I find it mean spirited.  Yes, perhaps the best thing is simply to ignore it.  Past experience suggests that solution doesn’t work.  See, e.g., the official board for CH, where the nasty comment/useful info ratio is about 9 to 1.  I ignore it on the official board because I think it’s a lost cause there.  It doesn’t seem like a lost cause here – I think these boards can remain a pleasant forum that exchanges useful information with a minimum of nastiness.  So when I see it here, I reply.  Especially since we have a rant board here, so that people who absolutely must vent in public have a place to do so.<br>
<br>
My objection is to people who fly off the handle and post melodramatic overreactions on inadequate data.  Reactions to the Thunderheart posts are a classic example.  As Vertexon says, “The CH Designer also wants to stress that these are proposed changes.  He has not changed a single thing yet, even internally.”  The proposed changes are being constantly revised.  Moreover, the initial post left considerable ambiguity<br>
<br>
Nevertheless, people fly off the handle immediately.  The pattern on the official boards is to assume instantly that each proposed change will manifest in its worst possible form and to have a hissy fit about that.  <br>
<br>
Allow me to illustrate with a few examples from joboosc’s enlightening follow-up post:<br>
<br>
>A Summary of nerf in the next update:<br>
>1. MAX callable level will be lowered from CL70 to CL60.<br>
<br>
That’s something they’re still working on.  That’s why it’s a PROPOSED change.  And therefore, why it makes no sense to fly off the handle yet.  From Vertexon’s post today: “Here's a question for you:  If the max creature level were to remain at 70, where would you put the +Lvl's in the skill tree?”<br>
<br>
Looks to me like they responded to the protests over reducing the max level.  Odd behavior for people who hate creature handlers.<br>
<br>
>2. There wont be any aggressive levels. One level system to determine usage.<br>
<br>
Correct, and completely unobjectionable.<br>
<br>
>3. Popular Tank pets like Webmasters, Kliknik Queens, Graul Mauler, Grauls, BDQs, GSP, Grand >Wrix, and Mereks etc. will be nerfed down with less HAM and resists.<br>
<br>
Actually, they may be nerfed down or they may have their CH level raised.  From Vertexon’s post today:  “with the creature balance pass changing the most grossly imbalanced creatures so that they are more or less equal to other creatures of their level (or raising their level until they are)”<br>
<br>
Especially since new pets are coming in, and extinct ones coming back, I fail to see why this is a problem.  Factor in the defensive power of pets and set their levels accordingly.  This suggestion has been out on the CH board for months.  Perfectly sensible.  If some have their power reduced, others will not, and new ones will come in.  After the changes, I fully expect a range of pets with different power and ability at different levels, instead of a single pet (graul mauler) with huge power at a low level.  Whether they say “grand wrix” over them or not is largely immaterial.<br>
<br>
That increases variety rather than decreases it, and increases strategy rather than decreases it.<br>
<br>
>4. There will be a stopgrowth command to stop the growth of your pet so you can use 2 half >grown rancors for instance. <br>
<br>
Sure.  And this is problematic why?  <br>
<br>
>5. MCH may still be able to solo Krayts with LLC, Flame thrower, or Pistoleer tree.<br>
<br>
Yet we need to quit because we’re all being nerfed to hell and back?<br>
<br>
>6. Agro system will be changed so AI will go after the creature handler rather than the pets. It >will also go after whoever deals the max damage or doing the healing like in EQ.<br>
<br>
No.  The AI will be changed to increase the chance of those things happening marginally.  For reference, Thunderheart’s exact words were:<br>
<br>
“NPCs and creatures will get just a tiny bit smarter, and will realize that when you send a pet to attack them, _you_ are attacking them.  This doesn't mean that they will instantly and always ignore your pet and head straight for you, but they won't just completely ignore you, either.  And if they kill your pet, they'll definitely be attacking you next.<br>
 <br>
Also, if you heal a pet that is fighting something else, that other creature will "see" it and might choose to respond to that action by attacking you.  Probably not a very big chance of that happening, but they won't just completely ignore you as they do now.”<br>
<br>
Bring some highlights back one more time, maestro:<br>
<br>
“just a tiny bit smarter”<br>
<br>
“This doesn't mean that they will instantly and always ignore your pet and head straight for you”<br>
<br>
“might choose to respond to that action by attacking you.  Probably not a very big chance of that happening”<br>
<br>
Those qualifiers mean it should happen some, but not a lot.  If the view is that Thunderheart is simply flat out lying, then I don’t imagine we have much ground to converse on.  I apply a presumption of good faith.  If the view is they’ll inevitably screw it up, I suppose I would like to see the warrant for that view.  Many mistakes happen in this game, yes, but the VAST MAJORITY of the game has functional and operative coding.  Lots of the variations from the EQ model have been coded successfully.  We notice the glitches, but on balance the programmers’ track record is good.<br>
<br>
>Results: The only profession that is still 'fun' to play in SWG, considered by many, will be no >fun to play at all. <br>
<br>
And we know this how?  Having not seen the changes?  Not even knowing what they will be, since the devs aren’t even sure yet?  <br>
<br>
Also, joboosc omits a number of other changes that promise to add significant fun factor to the class, including:<br>
<br>
1.  Addition of new pets and restoring some old extinct pets<br>
2.  Addition of rare spawn babies, to provide something akin to loot for the CH class<br>
3.  Addition of commands to call for specials and call for ranged attacks<br>
<br>
>PVP is a joke and will forever be a joke given the game design. <br>
<br>
/shrug.  Wouldn’t know, wouldn’t care.  I will freely confess this – I have flat out no interest in PVP whatever.  If joboosc’s complaints bear on PVP, then I have no comment.  I don’t do PVP or care about it.  If that’s the problem, I have nothing to offer and retract my comments.  I speak only to PVE.<br>
<br>
>Crafters will still run away with your money until the servers get overloaded with crafters.<br>
<br>
Are we playing the same game?  My credit per hour return running missions is about 3x most crafters.  The only reason crafters run away with my money is that I pay no attention at all to the rate they’re charging me.  My armorsmith could quadruple his prices & I wouldn’t care in the slightest.  Frankly, the only reason I take missions at all now is that I figure starships might cost a lot & it couldn’t hurt to save up a bunch of credits.<br>
<br>
>AND, last but not least, you will now need a group to kill a Bantha lair.<br>
<br>
Rhetorical excess serving no argumentative function.  And needing, thus, no reply.<br>
<br>
>You honestly say that the game is still fun? I wonder how much SWG devs are paying you to >post propaganda.<br>
<br>
This is exactly the kind of attitude and tone I’m talking about.  Anyone who disagrees with joboosc’s view is either (A) a dev who is clinically deaf, mentally retarded, and spiteful and malicious; or (B) one of their hired stooges; or (C) an unwitting dupe who needs the veil of complacency ripped from their eyes.<br>
<br>
How about a fourth option?  Someone who enjoys the game and doesn’t think his complaining has merit?  Novel though the thought may be, your viewpoint isn’t necessarily universal.  Yes, the game honestly is still fun to me.  I anticipate it being fun after the CH adjustments as well.  I could be wrong, but unlike joboosc I’m willing to make that judgment based on actual facts rather than hyperbole and overreaction.<br>
<br>
<br>
I agree with you that I don’t like seeing players go.  I especially don’t like seeing pleasant players who are fun to play with go.  None of the pleasant players I enjoy playing with are leaving.  Lots of l337 d00dz are, but that doesn’t bother me much.  I played EQ on the Nameless for years.  Every couple of months, Tigole (the Legacy of Steel guildleader) would announce that he was pissed about nerf X or nerf Y, and that he was quitting.  Reaction among myself and the people I played with was always the same:  don’t let the door hit you in the ass on the way out.  I feel the same way here.  I see an honest effort by the devs to balance an unbalanced profession, and I see a massive outpouring of nastiness, spite, and vituperation.  Unnecessary and unpleasant. <br>
